x4freetext: Folded Tandem Ion Accelerator (FOTIA)
facility
A double sided ionization chamber contains a
cathode and an anode made of copper plated G-10 discs
of diameter 7.0 cm each, were separated from each
other by 2.0 mm Teflon spacer rings used to generate
fission trigger.
The fission fragments produced in the 232Th(n,f)
reaction are detected in the fission chamber covering a
solid angle of nearly 4pi.
The generated electron-ion pairs give rise to an
electrical signal, which is used as a start pulse for
the time-of-flight measurement.
The prompt neutrons emitted in coincidence
with the fission fragments were measured.
The coincidence time resolution (FWHM) is estimated to
be ~ 6 ns
A natural lithium metallic target of thickness
4.0 mg/cm2.

x4freetext: Two 1.0 cm X 1.0 cm foils of 232Th of thickness
~ 2.0 mg/cm2
A neutron detectors EJ301 liquid scintillator
detectors (12.7 cm diameter and 5.0 cm thick) were
placed at a distance of about 1.0 m from the ionization
chamber and at angle of 55 and 60 degree with respect
to the  beam direction.
The detector efficiency and response function were
determined by GEANT4.

x4freetext: The prompt fission gamma-rays were measured by
two 38.1 mm X 38.1 mm cylindrical CeBr3 detectors.
The detector, optically coupled with Hamamatsu 50.8 mm
type R6231-100 photomultiplier tube placed at distances
of 24 cm and 26 cm from the ionization chamber.
The detector response function was determined by GEANT4
Fig.10 of Eur. Phys. J. A 56 (2020) 116
